('Fusion', 'A music genre that developed in the late 1960s when musicians combined jazz harmony and improvisation with rock music, funk, and rhythm and blues.'),
('Smooth Jazz', 'A commercially oriented genre of jazz that became dominant in the 1980s and early 1990s.'),
('Acid Jazz', 'A musical genre that combines elements of jazz, soul, funk, and disco.'),
('Free Jazz', 'An approach to jazz music that was first developed in the 1950s and 1960s as musicians attempted to alter, extend, or break down jazz convention.'),
('Ragtime', 'A musical style that enjoyed its peak popularity between 1895 and 1919. Its cardinal trait is its syncopated or "ragged" rhythm.'),
('Dixieland', 'A style of jazz music which developed in New Orleans at the start of the 20th century.'),
('Delta Blues', 'One of the earliest styles of blues music. It originated in the Mississippi Delta.'),
('Chicago Blues', 'A form of blues music that developed in Chicago, Illinois. It is based on earlier blues idioms, such as Delta blues, but performed in an urban style.'),
('Rhythm and Blues', 'A genre of popular music that originated in African American communities in the 1940s.'),
('Soul Jazz', 'A development of jazz incorporating strong influences from blues, soul, gospel and rhythm and blues.'),

-- CLASSICAL & ORCHESTRAL
('Classical', 'Art music produced or rooted in the traditions of Western culture, including both liturgical (religious) and secular music.'),
('Baroque', 'A period of Western art music composed from approximately 1600 to 1750.'),
('Romantic', 'A stylistic movement in Western orchestral music associated with the period of the 19th century commonly referred to as the Romantic era.'),
('Opera', 'A form of theatre in which music has a leading role and the parts are taken by singers, but is distinct from musical theatre.'),
('Symphony', 'An extended musical composition in Western classical music, most often written by composers for orchestra.'),
('Chamber Music', 'A form of classical music that is composed for a small group of instruments—traditionally a group that could fit in a palace chamber or a large room.'),
